  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Sarah Pugh begins this letter by asking: &quot;Have you any comfort for me other than &apos;Whatever is---is right&apos;?&quot; She complains of Oliver Johnson&apos;s &quot;&apos;airing&apos; of the troubles in our midst.&quot; She notes that William Lloyd Garrison has not copied the statements in the Liberator. Pugh says: &quot;The present conductors of the &apos;Standard&apos; have shown themselves in this case wise &amp; dignified in making no rejoinder, which I must confess I exceedingly dreaded their doing.&quot; She wishes to know Maria W. Chapman&apos;s views on the controversial issues. Sarah Pugh receieved letters from Mary A. Estlin and Harriet Lupton; their letters were written in Wales.</subfield>
